{{For|the Canadian comic strip|Weltschmerz (comic strip)}} [[File:Dalian Liaoning China An-elderly-Chinese-at-Xinghai-Bay-01.jpg|thumb|right]] '''''Weltschmerz''''' (from the German, literally ''world-pain'', also ''world weariness'', {{IPA-de|ˈvɛltʃmɛɐ̯ts|pron}}) is a term coined by the German author [[Jean Paul]] and denotes the kind of feeling experienced by someone who believes that physical reality can never satisfy the demands of the mind.{{cn|date=June 2018}} This kind of [[world view]] was widespread among several [[romanticism|romantic]] and [[decadent movement|decadent]] authors such as [[George Gordon Byron, 6th Baron Byron|Lord Byron]], [[Oscar Wilde]], [[William Blake]], the [[Marquis de Sade]], [[Charles Baudelaire]], [[Giacomo Leopardi]], [[Paul Verlaine]], [[François-René de Chateaubriand]], [[Alfred de Musset]], [[Mikhail Lermontov]], [[Nikolaus Lenau]],<ref name="Braun">{{cite book|last1=Braun|first1=Wilhelm Afred|title=Types of Weltschmerz in German Poetry|date=1905|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C58tAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=weltschmerz+heinrich+heine&source=bl&ots=TWO6WoD9bz&sig=N5V6VYVUmyW3GfPQbf_tSNeXGKE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA54Dq_YDMAhUC6yYKHSVdB-MQ6AEISDAF#v=onepage&q=weltschmerz%20heinrich%20heine&f=false|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> [[Hermann Hesse]],<ref name="Stelzig">{{cite book|last1=Stelzig|first1=Eugene L.|title=Hermann Hesse's Fictions of the Self: Autobiography and the Confessional Imagination|date=1988|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, NJ|isbn=0-691-06750-3|page=81|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nwQABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=weltschmerz+hermann+hesse&source=bl&ots=3Vgdf1LOxk&sig=_jzL8PW02vdf5liGPmk_TuTE5rI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-joSf_IDMAhUBQCYKHfh7AKY4ChDoAQgiMAE#v=onepage&q=weltschmerz%20hermann%20hesse&f=false|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> and [[Heinrich Heine]].<ref name="Braun"/>
[[Frederick C. Beiser]] defines ''Weltschmerz'' more broadly as "a mood of weariness or sadness about life arising from the acute awareness of evil and suffering",<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UiwRDAAAQBAJ |title=Weltschmerz: Pessimism in German Philosophy, 1860-1900 |last=Beiser |first=Frederick C. |date=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191081347 |pages=1}}</ref> and notes that by the 1860s the word was used ironically in Germany to refer to oversensitivity to those same concerns.
==Further examples== [[John Steinbeck]] wrote about this feeling in ''[[The Winter of Our Discontent]]'' and referred to it as the ''Welshrats''; and in ''[[East of Eden (novel)|East of Eden]]'', Samuel Hamilton feels it after meeting Cathy Trask for the first time. [[Ralph Ellison]] uses the term in ''[[Invisible Man]]'' with regard to the pathos inherent in the singing of spirituals: "beneath the swiftness of the hot tempo there was a slower tempo and a cave and I entered it and looked around and heard an old woman singing a spiritual as full of Weltschmerz as [[flamenco]]". [[Kurt Vonnegut]] references this feeling in his novel ''[[Player Piano (novel)|Player Piano]]''; it is felt by Doctor Paul Proteus and his father. In [[Henry Miller]]'s ''[[Tropic of Cancer (novel)|Tropic of Cancer]]'', he describes an acquaintance, "Moldorf", who has prescriptions for Weltschmerz on scraps of paper in his pocket.
